'''Kenner Products'''<ref name="Ultimate Action Figure Collection">''[[Star Wars: The Ultimate Action Figure Collection]]''</ref> was a post-[[Wikipedia:World War II|World War II]] era American toy company founded in 1947 by brothers Albert, Phillip, and Joseph L. Steiner, in Cincinnati, Ohio. Under subsequent ownership of the [[Wikipedia:General Mills|General Mills Group]] Kenner Products acquired a master license from [[Lucasfilm]] to produce all toys, games, and crafts based on the 1977 [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']] film.<ref name="Loomis">{{Rebelscum|url=loomis.asp|text=An Interview with Bernard Loomis, former president of Kenner|author=D. Martin Myatt|archivedate=20200605002455}}</ref>

Kenner, named after the street where the original corporate offices were located, manufactured a wide range of ''Star Wars''&ndash;branded toys, with the most popular being their line of basic 3¾-inch action figures.
==History==
{{Quote|Nathan, who is sixteen now, the first word I think he learned was 'Kenner'.|Mark Hamill, on the preponderance of ''Star Wars'' toys in their home, during an episode of the television show ''Personal FX''|<ref name="SWI29">{{InsiderCite|29|The Unsung Collectibles: Star Wars Magazines}}</ref>}}
The [[Star Wars (Kenner toy line)|''Star Wars'' toys]] were a big part of the wider commercial success of the merchandise, planned for early [[1978]]. In the holiday season of [[1977]], there was a big demand for toys, and Kenner sold empty "Early Bird Certificate Kits" for $16 that would be filled once the toys became commercially available. That year Kenner sold 42,322,500 units, with $100 million in revenue, making an impact in the subsequent licensing industry of the present times.<ref name="secrets">''[[The Secrets of Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire]]''</ref> The enormous popularity of ''Star Wars'' contributed to the doubling of the company's sales since 1975 (more than $200 million in '78).<ref name="Kenner History" /> 

The success continued in [[1980]], with [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''The Empire Strikes Back'']] line, and by [[1983]] more than 300 million ''Star Wars'' toys had been sold.<ref name="Kenner History" />
[[File:WooofFigure.png|thumb|left|A Klaatu figure]]
The action figures were hand-crafted and articulated. Some figures wore fabric capes.<ref name="secrets" /> There were 96 action figures released in the movie figure lines, though the final card back promoted a full line of 92 action figures. This is because when Kenner produced new versions (with new, unique product numbers) of R2-D2 and C-3PO action figures, they discontinued previous versions. One version of C-3PO and two versions of R2-D2 were discontinued. Also the [[Saelt-Marae/Legends|Yak Face]] figure was never available in the United States and was not pictured on the card backs.<ref name="VintageVault">{{WebCite|url=https://www.fanthatracks.com/news/collecting/how-many-star-wars-action-figures-are-therecollect-all-92-93-96-erm-star-wars-action-figures|text=Vintage Vault: Collect all 92! 93! 96! Erm? How many Star Wars action figures are there?|author=Hutchinson, Richard|date=2018-02-05|work=[https://www.fanthatracks.com Fantha Tracks]|archivedate=20200924015913}}</ref><ref name="Yak Face">{{KennerCite|set=Star Wars: The Power of the Force (1985 toy line)|text=''Star Wars: The Power of the Force'' (1985)|pack=Yak Face|link=vintyakface.asp}}</ref>

By 1985, Kenner had sold over 250 million figures.<ref name="YBYNE">''[[Star Wars Year By Year: A Visual History, New Edition]]''</ref> In 1985, Kenner Products merged with [[Parker Brothers]] to create '''Kenner Parker Toys''', and Kenner Parker Toys was subsequently acquired by the [[Wikipedia:Tonka|Tonka Corporation]] in 1987.<ref name="NYT">{{WebCite|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/05/business/kenner-takes-proposal-of-51-a-share-by-tonka.html|text=Kenner Takes Proposal of $51 a Share by Tonka|work=''The New York Times''|archiveurl=https://archive.is/fglCI}}</ref>

On [[February 1]], [[1991]], [[Hasbro]] acquired the Tonka Corporation, including Kenner,<ref name="YBYNE" /> and let the ''[[Star Wars]]'' license lapse due to a perceived lack of interest in ''Star Wars''.<ref name="SFChronicle">{{WebCite|url=https://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Hasbro-Adds-Galoob-to-Its-Toy-Chest-2988518.php|text=Hasbro Adds Galoob to Its Toy Chest|work=the ''San Francisco Chronicle''|date=1998-09-28|archiveurl=https://archive.is/wCxg}}</ref> Following a long hiatus, Hasbro relaunched its ''Star Wars'' line under the Kenner brand in 1995, with the release of a revived ''[[Star Wars: The Power of the Force (1995 toy line)|The Power of the Force]]'' collection.<ref name="Kenner History" /> These new figures were designed to be more appealing to children, with more active and aggressive poses. The capes were higher-quality vinyl.<ref name="secrets" />

The [[1996|next year]] Kenner produced figures for ''[[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire]]'' project,<ref name="secrets" /> elevating the ''Star Wars'' lines to second most popular (after ''Batman'') for a whole year.<ref name="Kenner History" />

After ''The Power of the Force'' and other subsequent releases, the Kenner logo was finally replaced with Hasbro branding in [[1999]]. 

Hasbro closed the Cincinnati offices of Kenner in [[2000]], and Kenner's product lines were merged into Hasbro's.<ref name="Kenner History" /> In later years, Kenner branding was revived for products with packaging reminiscent of the original toys, including ''[[Star Wars: The Vintage Collection]]'' and other series.

===In popular culture===
{{Quote|These are toys. These are little men. [He shows E.T. several ''Star Wars'' action figures.] This is Greedo, and then this is Hammerhead. See, this is Walrus Man, and this is Snaggletooth and this is Lando Calrissian. See? And this is Boba Fett. See.... and look, they can even have wars. Look at this. [He has the action figures 'shoot' each other.]|Elliot in ''E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial''|<ref name="ET">[[Wikipedia:E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial|''E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial'']]</ref>}}

In the 1982 film [[Wikipedia:E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial|''E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial'']], ''Star Wars'' action figures are included in a scene in which lead character Elliot introduces the alien "E.T." to objects in his everyday life.

In the 1994 [[Wikipedia:The Simpsons|''The Simpsons'']] episode "[[Wikipedia:Lisa's Rival|Lisa's Rival]]," Ralph Wiggum says "I bent my Wookiee" when he falls on his figure of [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]]. Ralph also enters a diorama of repackaged ''Star Wars'' action figures in a contest. His collection includes [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]], [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]], and Chewbacca.

